Friskie was an ecclesiastical parish founded in Western Shetland after the late 12th century, originally a Church-sponsored workhouse venture to provide for the growing underprivileged feline community within the region. Historically considered the foundational turnaround for the calico anthro, which was at threat of extinction by approximately the year 1300 due to inbreeding, significant poverty and intense social and religious objections to the greater feline willingness to take in a human spouse, a practice the calico people often considered miscegenation and culturally traitorous. Most historians now agree that this perception was brought upon by dwindling male calico birthrates and staunch religiosity. In 1838, under the First Littere Doctrine, Friskie was recorded with a population of 998, which saw significant rise over the ensuing decades as anti-human stigmas lessened.

In 1946, following the end of the Second Whippet War, Friskie was subsumed into the greater West Shetland area and rendered legally abolished, but the community would maintain a bold local identity for many more years petitioning to the city until the Calico Stalls Community Area was established in 1986, forty years to the date of Friskie's dissolution and named in honor of both the strong historical calico demography and the original provided workhouses, which were colloquially referred to as "stalls." In 2018, West Shetland elected it's first calico mayor, Tammy Brightmoor, a Calico Stalls native who would serve one term.

Personally I prefer the more psuedo-realistic approach where the offspring of Humans and Anthros create Human or Anthro offspring, regardless of the father's (or mother's) species.
So you'd have the possibility of a son who is Human or Anthro, or a daughter who is Human or Anthro. Despite what many say about preferring the kids to be Human men and Anthro women exclusively, I think the opposite still has its positives that are often overlooked. An Anthro son, despite being fuzzy all over, still inherits half of your genes, whether they pertain to your personality or your hair/eye color. Being the father, you will set an example to him and thus he will follow traditions and actions set forth by you, even during his teenage years and beyond. Likewise with a Human daughter. She also has the added benefit of being raised by an Anthro mother, which means she'll develop desirable mannerisms and traits that are less likely to be found in modern Human women.
Still, it's interesting to think about the Hybrid implications of interspecies breeding. My idea is that over time (let's say centuries), as more Humans and Anthros mix, both species begin to develop traits that don't belong to their base form.
For example, Humans with mixed blood could develop fangs, have nocturnal vision, or be hairier than the average Human. Anthros with mixed blood could have shorter tails, eyes that are more Human-like, regular legs, or if an Anthro is typically short, be unusually tall. These changes would become more prominent over time, and THEN we get Hybrids.
What do (you) think?
